\description{
These functions expose the logo-drawing machinery of \code{\link[=view_motifs]{view_motifs()}} and
\code{\link[=view_logo]{view_logo()}} as composable \pkg{ggplot2} layers, so a sequence logo can be
dropped into a plot you are already building (annotating a coverage track,
adding an inset to a scatter plot, placing a logo at every tip of a tree,
and so on) instead of being returned as a standalone plot.
}
\details{
There are two pairs. \code{geom_motif()} / \code{annotate_motif()} take a
\code{universalmotif} object (or anything \code{\link[=convert_motifs]{convert_motifs()}} accepts) and honour
\code{use.type} exactly like \code{\link[=view_motifs]{view_motifs()}}. \code{geom_logo()} / \code{annotate_logo()}
take a bare row-named numeric matrix with arbitrary values, like
\code{\link[=view_logo]{view_logo()}}. In each pair the \verb{annotate_*()} function places one logo at
fixed coordinates (no data or aesthetic inheritance), while the \verb{geom_*()}
function is a true layer whose position comes from aesthetics, so it picks
up faceting and can be driven from a data frame.

Letters are drawn as filled, borderless polygons whose colour is resolved
internally (so the layer never competes for the plot's \code{fill} scale and adds
no legend). Consequently the \code{colour}, \code{alpha}, and \code{linetype} aesthetics
have no effect; appearance is controlled only through \code{colour.scheme} (or
\code{fill} for the logo variants).

Two positioning modes are supported and chosen per row from the supplied
aesthetics:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Bounding box}: supply \code{xmin}, \code{xmax}, \code{ymin}, \code{ymax} (the model used by
\code{\link[ggplot2:annotation_custom]{ggplot2::annotation_custom()}}). The whole logo is rescaled into the box.
\item \strong{Anchored}: supply \code{x} (the left edge) and \code{y} (the vertical centre);
the box is then \code{xmin = x}, \code{xmax = x + ncol * width},
\code{ymin = y - height/2}, \code{ymax = y + height/2}. This is the natural fit for
placing logos at tree tips.
}

To draw several motifs aligned to a common column frame (for example a
stack of aligned logos, or aligned tip logos on a tree), align them first
with \code{\link[=view_motifs2]{view_motifs2()}} (or \code{\link[=view_motifs]{view_motifs()}}) and pass the result to
\code{geom_logo()}:

\preformatted{
aligned <- view_motifs2(motifs, return.raw = TRUE, use.type = "ICM",
                        sort.by = "none")
ggplot(tipdf, aes(x = 0, y = y, motif = label)) +
  geom_logo(logo = aligned, colour.scheme = DNA_COLOURS)
}
}
